---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const deepBad = `.page .content .card .header .title {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
}`;

const deepGood = `.product-card > .title {
    margin-block-end: var(--space);
}`;

const utilityBad = `<article class="p-l m-b-xl bg-dark text-light radius-m grid gap-m">
    ...
</article>`;

const utilityGood = `<article class="product-card product-card--featured">
    ...
</article>`;

const stateBad = `.button--loading {}
.button--active {}
.button--disabled {}`;

const stateGood = `.button {}
.button.is_loading {}
.button.is_disabled {}`;

const legacyLayerExample = `@layer legacy, settings, base, utilities,
layout, components, theme, hacks;`;

const hacksExample = `@layer hacks {
    .checkout-banner {
        margin-top: -3px;
    }
}`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="Examples Library"
    description="Practical before and after examples for Layered Semantic CSS."
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Examples</p>
        <h1>Show me, do not merely explain</h1>
        <p class="intro">
            Principles matter. Examples end arguments. These before and after
            patterns show what architectural improvement looks like in real CSS,
            not only in confident documentation.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Examples sections">
        <a href="#selectors">Deep selectors</a>
        <a href="#utilities">Utility overload</a>
        <a href="#state">Modifier vs state</a>
        <a href="#legacy">Legacy migration</a>
        <a href="#hacks">Temporary fixes</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="selectors" class="content-block">
        <h2>Deep selectors to shallow ownership</h2>

        <h3>Before</h3>
        <CodeExample code={deepBad} language="css" variant="before" />

        <h3>After</h3>
        <CodeExample code={deepGood} language="css" variant="after" />

        <p>
            Deep selectors couple CSS to markup structure. Short scoped
            selectors make ownership obvious and safe to change.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="utilities" class="content-block">
        <h2>Utility overload to semantic components</h2>

        <h3>Before</h3>
        <CodeExample code={utilityBad} language="html" variant="before" />

        <h3>After</h3>
        <CodeExample code={utilityGood} language="html" variant="after" />

        <p>
            Repeated utility stacks usually mean a component is trying to exist.
            Name it once instead of explaining it forever.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="state" class="content-block">
        <h2>State disguised as modifiers</h2>

        <h3>Before</h3>
        <CodeExample code={stateBad} language="css" variant="before" />

        <h3>After</h3>
        <CodeExample code={stateGood} language="css" variant="after" />

        <p>
            Permanent reusable variants are modifiers. Temporary UI behaviour
            should be visible as state.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="legacy" class="content-block">
        <h2>Legacy migration example</h2>

        <p>
            Do not move old CSS into new components and call it progress.
            Create a legacy layer first, then improve active work safely.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={legacyLayerExample} language="css" />

        <p>
            Legacy should stay visible and low priority, not quietly spread.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="hacks" class="content-block">
        <h2>Temporary fixes becoming permanent residents</h2>

        <p>
            If a hack will still exist in six months, it is probably a real fix
            pretending to be temporary.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={hacksExample} language="css" />

        <p>
            Keep hacks visible. Hidden hacks become architecture by accident.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>Next useful pages</h2>

        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/learn/anti-pattern-gallery/">Anti-pattern gallery</a></h3>
                <p>Recognise the bad patterns before they become normal.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/apply/decision-trees/">Decision trees</a></h3>
                <p>Use practical rules when deciding how to improve code.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3><a href="/apply/audit-checklist/">Audit checklist</a></h3>
                <p>Review existing codebases using the same standards shown here.</p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
